description: 2 black Wolves trying to scare the bear off a Bison so they could get a bite. It didn't work, he held his ground. They never really seemed to be fighting, just exchanging dirty looks. at one point they were so close it looked like the were touching. After awhile they all just took a nap, but eventually the wolves left.

I am quite certain this is a Wolf track because it was in the National Park where dogs are not permitted, and it had rained the night before, so I could see all the other human tracks at the trail head,and no dog tracks. Also they were HUGE,my hand is 7"in. long,so about 5"in, long by 3"in. wide. Only the largest dogs like a mastiff would have tracks that big. Wolves have larger paws in proportion to a dog of the same size,which helps them stay on top of the snow. But still this was probably a big male wolf,probably over 120lbs. There were tracks of all different sizes,meaning a whole pack had gone threw the night before. This was only about a mile or so from my camp. Unfortunately I didn't hear them howl though. Apparently they don't howl much this time of year to keep their pups hidden.

I believe these are Wolf tracks because they are too big(5"X3") to be any but the largest breed of dog, and although the shepherds here do keep Great Pyrenees, they have been gone since before the snow fell, and there would also be horse(which the shepherds ride) and sheep  tracks associated,which there were not. If it was someone walking their dog, there would be human tracks nearby too,which there were not,beside I have never seen my neighbors ever walk their dog around here. Also there were many tracks of different sizes,implying an entire pack,with pups. 2 years ago, on an October night while stargazing here ,I heard a Wolf howl,very close,probably down by the creek a few hundred yards distant. I have heard them howl before in Yellowstone and am certain no coyote or dog could have made that long,low deep howl. Then last winter,just over the ridge in Diamond Fork less than 5 miles away,Wildlife Services gunners looking for Coyotes,spotted 4 wolves, it was a big deal and all over the news at the time At first you would think this area wouldn't be a good place for wolves,lots of trigger happy rednecks everywhere(I wont even go up there on a weekend),and in the summer they run a ton of cattle and sheep there,but the thing is,the dense aspen forest around here have a TON of Elk and Deer in summer,and this valley lies at a crossroads,with the vast wilderness of the Uintas to the north,the rugged Wasatch to the west, and the high plateaus to the south,which are also teaming with Elk, its a great place for wolves to call home,and potentially disperse throughout the high country of the state. So far they have mostly stayed out of trouble with livestock,which is a miracle considering how many range maggots(sheep) they put up here in summer. Lets just hope the feds retain control of wolves in Utah under the endangered species act,because if they get handed over to the state,the legislature will pass some dumbass law mandating their extermination to appease the hunting and livestock lobby who they are in the pocket of. Oh wait a minute,they already did pass such a law. Idiots.

description: Feeding on an elk

This was by far the highlight of the time I spent in Yellowstone. After about a half hour of scoping out Lamar Valley I was about to head out when I decided to give myself another 15 minutes. About 5 minutes after that I saw one lone wolf emerge from the treeline. He eventually approached a group of bison making them nervous and defensive and decided to go on his way. He later ran up on a group of pronghorn but didn't pursue any as they ran away. After awhile the NPS wolf crew showed up so I'm assuming he has a collar on that you cant see in the photos. All of the photos were shot at 130x zoom or greater, the best I could manage.

The wolves turned off the plowed road  and jumped up onto an unplowed logging road that was covered with 4 feet of snow to follow what seems to be a traditional wolf route. Wolves have travelled this route several times before.

Saw this radio collared wolf eating the carcass of an undetermined animal, then disappearing over the ridge line. Wolf watchers weren't sure, but thought this might be 969F from the Junction Butte Pack: https://www.yellowstonewolf.org/yellowstone_wolf.php?wolf_id=90

Saw this wolf running up Specimen Ridge and disappearing into the trees. The wolf is radio collared, but no one IDed the wolf. Presumably this is another member of the Junction Butte Pack: https://www.yellowstonewolf.org/yellowstones_wolves.php?pack_id=3

This is the radio collared alpha female of the Junction Butte pack, 907F (https://www.yellowstonewolf.org/yellowstone_wolf.php?wolf_id=89). She’s been fighting her sister, the beta, for dominance and the wolf watchers think the sister killed all her pups in the den. The bison carcass was believed to be a kill made by the Junction Butte Pack the prior evening. After the wolf left, a coyote very nervously slunk in to feed looking up every few minutes to check if wolves were around. Other observations:

Bison: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/25298912
Ravens: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/25298984
Coyote: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/25299337/edit
This wolf wasn't radio collared or IDed. It's most likely part of the Junction Butte Pack since it's near the Junction Butte den: https://www.yellowstonewolf.org/yellowstones_wolves.php?pack_id=3

Finally got a good wolf video this morning. Took a few tries
OR30 wolf pack including OR30, 3 black and 3 gray wolves. OR30 is the wolf sitting in the fourth photo with a gray wolf sitting to the photo left and a black wolf walking past to the photo right.
A member of the OR30 wolf pack howling for 5-10 minutes before running off and disappearing.

These are not the prints of the animal that our team has tracked at Cedar Creek on-and-off over the past several years. These tracks are smaller and have different proportions. There have been a few trail camera photos of a second wolf in the area--a smaller, younger animal. These may be its prints. Stride length in a side-trot ranged from 140-160cm. Or perhaps they are the tracks of the most wolf-like house dog ever seen in Minnesota. We trailed the animal for about a mile. It consistently displayed wolf-like movement and behavior: investigating deer trails, but otherwise moving in a purposeful side-trot. For additional observations from this trail, see:

3.5” print, each stride 31” marked by 65” skate pole. Track was made during the night in a remote ski area north of town. Trail entered the packed ski trail out of the woods, followed it for over a mile, then went back into the woods, came out, more tracks, then back into the woods and gone. Linear pattern shown on stride photo continued throughout.
